# Normalize line endings to LF in the repo and in the working tree.
#
# Why: this repo is developed on Windows, Linux, and macOS. Without an
# explicit policy Git's `core.autocrlf=true` (the Windows default) flips
# CRLF on checkout and LF on commit, which fights every formatter we run
# (rustfmt, biome, etc.). The fight shows up as `git status` noise —
# files marked "modified" with no real diff — and as the persistent
#   warning: in the working copy of 'X', LF will be replaced by CRLF
# during every git operation.
#
# Policy:
#   * text=auto   → Git auto-detects text vs binary
#   * eol=lf      → text files are LF in the index AND in the working tree,
#                   regardless of `core.autocrlf` on the user's machine

* text=auto eol=lf

# Windows-specific scripts must keep CRLF or cmd/PowerShell will reject them.
*.bat       text eol=crlf
*.cmd       text eol=crlf
*.ps1       text eol=crlf

# Binary assets — never touch.
*.png       binary
*.jpg       binary
*.jpeg      binary
*.gif       binary
*.webp      binary
*.ico       binary
*.svg       text eol=lf
*.pdf       binary
*.zip       binary
*.gz        binary
*.tar       binary
*.7z        binary
*.woff      binary
*.woff2     binary
*.ttf       binary
*.otf       binary
*.eot       binary
*.mp3       binary
*.mp4       binary
*.webm      binary
*.wasm      binary

# Rust-specific: Cargo.lock is text but should not have merge driver tweaks.
Cargo.lock  text eol=lf
